{
  "text": "The AOC analysis monitors the potential hazards of an agricultural season that could threaten: a) crop yield, b) crop harvested area, or c) grain quality. a) Crop yield is the result of the interaction between genetic, environment and management [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . AOC analysis considers crops as genetically adapted to the environment, and thus deals only with weather events that, influencing crop growth and the management, potentially reduce the expected yields [CITATION_3] . b) In terms of crop harvested area, the inter-annual variability is mostly due to socio-economic reasons [CITATION_4] or relates to medium to long term trends, like climate change [CITATION_5] . The AOC analysis focuses only on those short-term meteorological events that could reduce the harvested area like frost kill or severe drought. c) The JRC MARS Bulletin does not have a specific focus on grain quality monitoring; nevertheless, weather conditions that could cause a significant quality reduction [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] are considered and mapped in the AOC analysis.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "73565156",
